#compdef figma-developer-mcp
# =============================================================================
# figma-developer-mcp — Model Context Protocol server that exposes Figma
#                       layout, design tokens, image assets, and component
#                       hierarchies to AI coding agents (Cursor, Claude Code,
#                       Windsurf, Cline, etc.) over the MCP transport.
#                       The agent fetches Figma file structure as compact
#                       YAML/JSON instead of expensive PDF/PNG screenshots,
#                       enabling pixel-precise "design-to-code" workflows
#                       without context window blowup.
#
# Author:  Graham Lipsman (GLips)
# Source:  https://github.com/GLips/Figma-Context-MCP
# CLI:     src/bin.ts (uses cleye)
# Library: privatenumber/cleye
#          ("👁‍🗨 Strongly typed CLI development for Node.js")
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active production — 14,931+ stars (one of the most-starred MCP
#          servers); npm package `figma-developer-mcp` with weekly downloads
#          in the tens of thousands; used in editor plugins for Cursor,
#          Claude Code, Windsurf, and Cline.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 25
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 25TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs from
# 24 to 25 documented libraries (cleye via figma-developer-mcp).  New
# leaderboard: Go=25, Rust=25, TypeScript-Node=25 — THREE-WAY TIE RESTORED
# at the top.  Taxonomy now spans 211 cross-language CLI library variants
# across 50 documented languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS cleye AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 25TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY VARIANT?
#
# cleye (https://github.com/privatenumber/cleye, 662+ stars) is **Hiroki
# Osame's** (privatenumber) command-line library for Node.js TypeScript
# development.  Hiroki is one of the most prolific Node.js tooling authors
# of the last five years: also author of tsx (TypeScript execute, npm
# alternative to ts-node — 9k+ stars), pkgroll (zero-config build tool —
# 1k+ stars), comment-mark (semantic markdown insertion — 500+ stars),
# tasuku (CLI task UI), get-tsconfig, premove, and many other
# small composable Node tools.  All of his CLIs use cleye internally.
#
# cleye's design is built on top of `type-flag` (also privatenumber, 200+
# stars) — type-flag is the pure parsing primitive; cleye is the user-
# facing CLI library that adds help text, usage formatting, subcommands,
# and ergonomic factories.
#
# cleye is DISTINCT from every other TS-Node CLI library documented in the
# corpus on six specific axes:
#
#   1. TYPE CONSTRUCTORS AS PARSE FUNCTIONS — cleye uses native JS type
#      constructors (`String`, `Number`, `Boolean`, `Array`) as the
#      runtime parser function AND the static type token.  When you write
#      `{ port: { type: Number } }`, TypeScript infers `port: number` for
#      the parsed argv.flags type, and Number(value) is the runtime parser.
#      Compare to:
#        commander.js: `program.option("--port <n>")` with no type info
#        yargs: `.option("port", { type: "number" })` with string literal
#        clipanion: `@Option({ type: "string" })` decorator
#        kong (Go, R465): struct tag `${name}:string` plus reflection
#        clap-derive (Rust, R275): proc macro reading struct field types
#      cleye's "Type constructor IS the schema" is unique among documented
#      TS-Node libraries.
#
#   2. POSITIONAL PARAMETERS VIA BRACKET-SYNTAX STRINGS — cleye declares
#      positionals via a `parameters: ["[url]", "<file>", "[extras...]"]`
#      array where:
#        "<name>"     required positional
#        "[name]"     optional positional
#        "[name...]"  variadic optional positional
#        "<name...>"  variadic required positional
#      This is closer to docopt syntax than to imperative builder calls.
#      Distinct from commander's `.argument("<file>")` chains, yargs'
#      `.positional()` builder, and oclif's `Args.string({ name: "file" })`.
#
#   3. SUBCOMMANDS VIA `command()` FACTORY — instead of a method on the
#      parser (`app.command(...)` in commander/yargs), cleye uses a
#      separate `command({ name, description, parameters, flags }, handler)`
#      factory function that returns a `Command` object.  Commands are
#      registered by passing `commands: [...]` to `cli()`.  This is more
#      composable: subcommands are first-class values that can be exported
#      from separate modules and reassembled at the top-level.
#
#   4. NO IMPLICIT EXECUTION — calling `cli({...})` parses argv and returns
#      a typed result object.  If a subcommand matched, its handler runs
#      DURING the `cli()` call, but the top-level handler is the
#      RESPONSIBILITY OF THE CALLER (typically guarded by
#      `if (!argv.command) { ... }`).  Compare to commander where
#      `.parse(argv)` invokes `.action()` callbacks; cleye is more
#      functional and lets the caller control flow.
#
#   5. CAMELCASE-TO-KEBAB-CASE FLAG CONVERSION — flag declarations use
#      CamelCase in TypeScript (`figmaApiKey`, `skipImageDownloads`,
#      `noTelemetry`) but the CLI surface uses kebab-case
#      (`--figma-api-key`, `--skip-image-downloads`, `--no-telemetry`).
#      The mapping is automatic — TypeScript developers don't have to
#      duplicate the name in two cases.  Most TS-Node libraries either
#      use the literal name (commander, yargs) or require manual aliasing.
#
#   6. INTEGRATION WITH HIROKI'S TOOL CHAIN — cleye is designed to work
#      seamlessly with tsx for development (`tsx src/bin.ts` runs
#      TypeScript directly) and pkgroll for production (`pkgroll`
#      produces a single ESM+CJS bundle).  The bin shebang is typically
#      `#!/usr/bin/env node` with the TypeScript precompiled to JS.
#      No other TS CLI library is as tightly coupled to a specific
#      build/dev toolchain — cleye + tsx + pkgroll is a cohesive
#      tooling story.
#
# THE cleye API SURFACE (verbatim from figma-developer-mcp/src/bin.ts)
#
#   import { cli } from "cleye";
#
#   const argv = cli({
#       name: "figma-developer-mcp",
#       version: process.env.NPM_PACKAGE_VERSION ?? "unknown",
#       flags: {
#           figmaApiKey:    { type: String,  description: "..." },
#           port:           { type: Number,  description: "..." },
#           json:           { type: Boolean, description: "..." },
#           skipImageDownloads: { type: Boolean, description: "..." },
#       },
#       commands: [fetchCommand],
#   });
#
#   // argv.flags.figmaApiKey      : string | undefined
#   // argv.flags.port             : number | undefined
#   // argv.flags.json             : boolean | undefined
#   // argv.command                : string | undefined  (subcommand name)
#   // argv._                      : string[]           (positionals)
#
# Subcommand factory:
#
#   import { command, type Command } from "cleye";
#
#   export const fetchCommand: Command = command(
#       {
#           name: "fetch",
#           description: "Fetch simplified Figma data",
#           parameters: ["[url]"],
#           flags: {
#               fileKey: { type: String, description: "..." },
#               nodeId:  { type: String, description: "..." },
#               depth:   { type: Number, description: "..." },
#           },
#       },
#       (argv) => {
#           run(argv.flags, argv._);
#       },
#   );
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER TS-NODE CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * commander.js               — fluent builder method chain
#   * yargs                      — chainable builder + handler dispatch
#   * minimist                   — pure argv parser, no help
#   * vercel/arg                 — small typed parser
#   * meow                       — opinionated CLI helper (yargs wrap)
#   * mri                        — minimist successor by lukeed
#   * caporal                    — declarative + plugin
#   * nopt                       — npm's classic parser
#   * cmd-ts                     — type-safe TS CLI builder
#   * clipanion                  — class+decorator (Yarn 2)
#   * citty (UnJS)               — defineCommand minimal
#   * cac                        — chainable typed
#   * sade                       — lukeed minimal
#   * type-flag                  — typed flag parser (cleye underlies on this)
#   * dthree/vorpal (R442)       — REPL-style interactive
#   * gluegun                    — full framework
#   * @stricli/core (R466)       — Bloomberg, zero-dep declarative
#   * cleye (THIS)               — TypeScript-first, type-constructor schema,
#                                  bracket-syntax positionals, command factory
#
# REAL-WORLD cleye USERS:
#
#   * GLips/Figma-Context-MCP — 14,931 stars (THIS completion)
#   * di-sukharev/AI-TDD — TDD-driven AI code generation (276 stars)
#   * vladkens/apigen-ts — TypeScript OpenAPI client generator (54 stars)
#   * jellydn/twt-dl-cli — Twitter video downloader (51 stars)
#   * Coldsewoo/airelease — AI-driven release notes generator
#   * Vindexus/MonorepoStarter — monorepo scaffolder
#   * agorischek/check-1-2 — CLI consistency checker
#   * sonyarianto/jogja, sonyarianto/dauh — Indonesian dev tools
#   * iamkhan21/getbump, iamkhan21/coode — micro-frontend tooling
#   * Most of privatenumber's own toolchain (tsx, pkgroll, etc.)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# FIGMA-DEVELOPER-MCP'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from src/bin.ts + commands/fetch.ts)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   figma-developer-mcp [<global-flags>]            Start MCP server
#   figma-developer-mcp fetch [url] [<fetch-flags>] Fetch data and print
#
# Global flags (start the MCP server):
#   --figma-api-key <key>      Figma API key (Personal Access Token)
#   --figma-oauth-token <tok>  Figma OAuth Bearer token
#   --env <path>               Path to custom .env file
#   --port <n>                 Port to run the server on
#   --host <host>              Host to run the server on
#   --json                     Output data from tools in JSON (alias --format=json)
#   --format <fmt>             Output format: yaml (default), json, tree
#   --skip-image-downloads     Don't register download_figma_images tool
#   --image-dir <dir>          Base directory for image downloads
#                              (defaults to CWD; download tool only writes
#                              files within this dir)
#   --proxy <url>              HTTP proxy URL (pass 'none' to bypass
#                              HTTP_PROXY/HTTPS_PROXY env vars)
#   --stdio                    Run in stdio transport mode (for MCP clients)
#   --no-telemetry             Disable usage telemetry (on by default)
#
# fetch subcommand flags (fetch Figma data and print to stdout):
#   --file-key <key>           Figma file key (overrides URL)
#   --node-id <id>             Node ID, format 1234:5678 (overrides URL)
#   --depth <n>                Tree traversal depth
#   --json                     Output JSON instead of YAML (alias --format=json)
#   --format <fmt>             Output format: yaml (default), json, tree
#   --figma-api-key <key>      Figma API key
#   --figma-oauth-token <tok>  Figma OAuth token
#   --env <path>               Path to .env file
#   --no-telemetry             Disable usage telemetry
#
# Positional (fetch subcommand):
#   [url]                      Figma URL to fetch (e.g.
#                              https://www.figma.com/file/abc/Title?node-id=1:2)
#
# Environment variables (also accepted via .env file):
#   FIGMA_API_KEY              Figma API key
#   FIGMA_OAUTH_TOKEN          Figma OAuth token
#   NODE_ENV=cli               Legacy backdoor enabling stdio transport
#   HTTP_PROXY, HTTPS_PROXY    HTTP proxy URLs (read unless --proxy=none)
#   NPM_PACKAGE_VERSION        Version string shown by --version
#
# =============================================================================

_figma-developer-mcp() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a subcommands global_flags fetch_flags formats

    subcommands=(
        'fetch:fetch simplified Figma data and print to stdout'
    )

    formats=(
        'yaml:YAML output (default)'
        'json:JSON output'
        'tree:experimental compact tree format'
    )

    global_flags=(
        '--figma-api-key[Figma API key (Personal Access Token)]:key:'
        '--figma-oauth-token[Figma OAuth Bearer token]:token:'
        '--env[path to custom .env file]:env file:_files'
        '--port[port to run the server on]:port:_ports'
        '--host[host to run the server on]:host:_hosts'
        '--json[output tool data in JSON (alias --format=json)]'
        '--format[output format]:format:->fmt'
        '--skip-image-downloads[do not register download_figma_images tool]'
        '--image-dir[base directory for image downloads]:dir:_directories'
        '--proxy[HTTP proxy URL (pass "none" to bypass env)]:proxy:'
        '--stdio[run in stdio transport mode for MCP clients]'
        '--no-telemetry[disable usage telemetry]'
        '--help[show help and exit]'
        '--version[show version and exit]'
    )

    fetch_flags=(
        '--file-key[Figma file key (overrides URL)]:file key:'
        '--node-id[Node ID, format 1234:5678 (overrides URL)]:node id:'
        '--depth[tree traversal depth]:depth:'
        '--json[output JSON instead of YAML]'
        '--format[output format]:format:->fmt'
        '--figma-api-key[Figma API key]:key:'
        '--figma-oauth-token[Figma OAuth token]:token:'
        '--env[path to .env file]:env file:_files'
        '--no-telemetry[disable usage telemetry]'
        '--help[show help and exit]'
        ':figma URL:'
    )

    _arguments -C \
        '1: :->cmd_or_flag' \
        '*::arg:->args' && ret=0

    case $state in
        (cmd_or_flag)
            _alternative \
                'subcommands:subcommand:(($subcommands))' \
                'global-flags:flag:(($global_flags))' \
                && ret=0
            ;;
        (args)
            case $line[1] in
                (fetch)
                    _arguments $fetch_flags && ret=0
                    ;;
                (*)
                    _arguments $global_flags && ret=0
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    case $state in
        (fmt)
            _describe -t formats 'output format' formats && ret=0
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_figma-developer-mcp "$@"
